01:00.562 --> 01:03.282
This seems a rather expensive
enterprise, Mr Selfridge.

01:03.322 --> 01:06.402
It will more than pay for itself.
How will we get it in the window?

01:06.442 --> 01:08.642
Don't worry about that.
Henri's an old hand.

01:08.682 --> 01:10.842
We'll dismantle it
and then put it together.

01:10.882 --> 01:14.862
My God! It worked like a dream
for us at Marshall Field.

01:14.911 --> 01:16.671
But back then,

01:16.711 --> 01:21.071
there were only 1,500 registered
drivers in the whole of Chicago.

01:21.111 --> 01:26.151
In London today, there are over
36,000. They'll come, they'll see,

01:26.191 --> 01:28.991
they'll walk inside
and they'll buy the products.

01:29.031 --> 01:30.871
Isn't she a beauty?

01:30.911 --> 01:34.551
This automobile is not insured
for anyone to drive.

01:34.591 --> 01:36.791
Not even you, Mr Selfridge.

01:36.831 --> 01:38.831
Ah!

01:38.871 --> 01:41.191
What do you think?

01:41.231 --> 01:43.871
Magnificent!
How is the window shaping up?

01:43.911 --> 01:46.871
"Motoring for the Modern Age!"

01:46.911 --> 01:49.511
Well, I miss Agnes Towler's
keen eye.

01:49.551 --> 01:51.351
So get her to work with you.

01:52.391 --> 01:54.071
I can't. She's gone.

01:54.991 --> 01:56.751
Gone?

01:56.791 --> 01:58.911
What? Didn't you know?

01:58.951 --> 02:02.031
After that business with her father,
she has left.

02:05.591 --> 02:08.110
Well, at least
George is still in work.

02:08.911 --> 02:11.071
Without his wages,
I don't know where we'd be.

02:12.111 --> 02:15.471
You'll look out for him, won't you?
Course I will.

02:17.431 --> 02:19.551
My dad's come back.

02:19.591 --> 02:21.271
I thought you'd changed the locks?

02:22.391 --> 02:26.511
He turned up last night, drunk,
passed out on the stairs.

02:26.551 --> 02:29.311
My landlady told me
if I didn't get him out of the way,

02:29.351 --> 02:31.871
that we'd all be out.
We'll have to work out something.

02:31.911 --> 02:34.911
He can't stay here forever.
I've been thinking...

02:34.951 --> 02:36.991
maybe it's not so bad
you left your job.

02:38.591 --> 02:40.431
What?
Well, for you and me.

02:40.471 --> 02:42.431
We can go out together now.

02:42.471 --> 02:45.151
How about we go down
to Brighton this weekend?

02:45.191 --> 02:48.151
Brighton? What would we do there?

02:48.191 --> 02:53.351
Walk on the beach, go down the pier,
hold hands in the moonlight.

02:53.391 --> 02:56.711
I know you're trying to cheer me up,
but I'm not in the mood.

02:56.751 --> 02:59.471
I'm asking if I can court you.

02:59.511 --> 03:01.631
That's what I'm doing!

03:02.791 --> 03:04.471
Oh, I see.

03:04.511 --> 03:06.511
Hadn't it crossed your mind at all?

03:07.711 --> 03:09.391
Not really.

03:10.751 --> 03:12.711
Well, maybe a bit...

03:12.751 --> 03:15.871
A bit?
Well, I suppose that's a start.

03:17.031 --> 03:20.791
I like you, Victor, you know I do.

03:20.831 --> 03:23.511
But I'm more trouble than I'm worth.

03:23.551 --> 03:27.911
What with George and my dad,
and me without a job.

03:29.831 --> 03:31.831
You don't want to court me.

03:31.871 --> 03:34.951
I do. More than anything.

